**![](data:image/png;base64,)**The action icons displayed at the top of the Flat File Writer's configuration page allow to perform global actions on the data structure.

**Icon**

**Action**

**Description**

![](data:image/png;base64,)

[**Import structure**](/doxee-platform/docs/4-dt3-flat-file-writer-global-actions#importing-a-data-schema)

Define the structure to write the output files using an existing XML or XSD file.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Download structure**

Download a copy of the data structure to your local filesystem in XML format (for example: *Writer_structure.xml*).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

[**Settings**](/doxee-platform/docs/4-dt3-flat-file-writer-global-actions#configuring-the-flat-file-writers-general-settings)

Define the general settings of the Flat File Writer's output file.

### Importing a data schema
This feature allows to define the structure to read input Flat files using an existing XML or XSD file.

The functionality is useful, for example, if you want to import the structure of an existing XML file instead of manually defining the required elements and attributes.

> Note

It is always possible to modify the imported structure.

> Warning

This action will permanently delete and overwrite the existing data structure.

- Open the Flat File Writer resource in the configuration editor as described in [Configuring DT3 Project Resources.](/doxee-platform/docs/configuring-dt3-project-resources)

- Click ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Import structure**). The system notifies you that uploading a structure file will discard the existing structure.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Click **Yes, continue **to proceed.

- Select the required XML or XSD file to upload using the file browser.

- The **Add structure template **dialog window is displayed:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- In the **Structure name **field, enter "**FlatFile_Writer**".

- Click **CONFIRM**. The new data structure is automatically loaded into the Flat File Writer's configuration, overwriting the existing data structure.

### Configuring the Flat File Writer's general settings
This feature allows to define the writer settings for the fields in the data structure, such as elements and attributes, and other general writer settings for the output flat file, such as for example indentation settings and line separators.

> Note

The system applies the writer settings to all elements and attributes that do not have custom writing settings.

For more information on defining custom writer settings, see: [DT3 Flat File Writer - Settings tab](/doxee-platform/docs/2-dt3-flat-file-writer-settings-tab).

- Open the Flat File Writer resource in the configuration editor as described in [Configuring DT3 Project Resources.](/doxee-platform/docs/configuring-dt3-project-resources)

- Click ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Settings**). The **Settings **panel is displayed on the right; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Configure the required parameters:

**Section**

**Parameter**

**Description**

**General**

**Name**

Name of the Flat File Writer

**Description**

*(optional) *Brief description of the Flat File Writer

**Element formatting**

**Alignment**

Select the alignment of the data in the fixed structure records of the flat file:

**Left: **Align the value to the left, adding a filler character to the right.

- **Right: **Align the value to the right, adding a filler character to the left.

**Text qualifier**

Select the separator character that you want to use to delimit fields containing text strings. The available options are:

- **None **

- **'**

- **"**

**Delimited**

Select this option to define the writer settings using a separator character.

From the corresponding drop-down menu, select the separator character that you want to use. The available options are:

- **None **

- **Tab**

- **|**

**Fixed**

Select this option to define the writer settings using a fixed-size field.

> Note

The system defines the length of the field based on the properties of the element contained in the input data schema.

From the corresponding drop-down menu, select the **Padding **character that you want to use. The available options are:

- **Zero **

- **Space**

> Note

If a field has a fewer characters than its fixed length, padding characters allow to reach the fixed length.

**Attribute formatting**

**Alignment**

Select the alignment of the data in the fixed structure records of the flat file:

- **Left: **Align the value to the left, adding a filler character to the right.

- **Right: **Align the value to the right, adding a filler character to the left.

**Text qualifier**

Select the separator character that you want to use to delimit fields containing text strings. The available options are:

- **None **

- **'**

- **"**

**Delimited**

Select this option to define the writer settings using a separator character.

From the corresponding drop-down menu, select the separator character that you want to use. The available options are:

- **None **

- **Tab**

- **|**

**Fixed**

Select this option to define the writer settings using a fixed-size field.

> Note

The system defines the length of the field based on the properties of the attribute contained in the input data schema.

From the corresponding drop-down menu, select the **Padding **character that you want to use. The available options are:

- **Zero **

- **Space**

> Note

If a field has a fewer characters than its fixed length, padding characters allow to reach the fixed length.

**Other settings**

**Enable indent**

Select this option to use indentation when writing the flat file, in order to make it more readable.

From the corresponding drop-down menu, select the required **Indentation character**. The available options are:

- **None**: Do not use an indentation character.

- **Tab**: Use tabulation as an indentation character.

**Line separator**

Select the character that you want to use as a line terminator when writing the flat file. The available options are:

- **None**: Do not use any line separator.

- **CR: **Line separator used on MacOS systems.

- **LF: **Line separator used on Unix systems.

- **CR + LF: **Line separator used on DOS and Windows systems.

**Scope**

In the **Scope **field, enter a description of the scope of the output flat file.

> Note

The system reports the description of the scope in the processing completion logs.

**Schema**

**Schema name**

View and edit the name of the current data schema.

**Manage schemas**

Click on this link to manage the available data schema, as described in [Managing data schemas](/doxee-platform/docs/4-dt3-flat-file-writer-global-actions#managing-data-schemas) below.

> Tip

The **Applied to **section lists the Data Transformation components using this data schema, allowing you to evaluate the impacts of adding, deleting or modifying its elements.

#### Managing data schemas
- Click on the **Manage schemas **link to open the dedicated panel; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Move your mouse over the name of a data schema to display the context actions; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Select one of the available actions:

**Icon**

**Action**

**Description**

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Download**

Download the data schema to your local filesystem.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Rename**

Edit the name of the data schema.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Delete**

Permanently remove the data schema from the project.

> Warning

This action cannot be undone.

If a data schema is currently used by one or more project components, this action is not available.

- If a data schema is used by one or more project components, a blue dot is displayed next to it. Click on it to see which resources are using the structure; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

A detail panel listing the resources already using the selected structure is displayed; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Tip

Click on the name of a resource to open it in its dedicated editor.

It is also possible to download or rename the data schema from this panel.
